This is a known pain point. Android deprecated `adjustResize` (API 30+), and .NET 10's default **edge-to-edge** mode changes how window insets work. Here's the modern fix:

## 1. Ensure `AdjustResize` is set on your Activity

In `Platforms/Android/MainActivity.cs`:

```csharp
[Activity(/* existing attributes */, WindowSoftInputMode = SoftInput.AdjustResize)]
public class MainActivity : MauiAppCompatActivity { }
```

## 2. Handle IME insets (the key fix for .NET 10)

With edge-to-edge, you must react to keyboard insets yourself. In your `MauiProgram.cs`, add an Android-specific handler that applies bottom padding when the keyboard appears:

```csharp
#if ANDROID
using AndroidX.Core.View;
using Microsoft.Maui.Platform;
#endif

// In CreateMauiApp():
builder.ConfigureMauiHandlers(handlers =>
{
#if ANDROID
    Microsoft.Maui.Handlers.PageHandler.Mapper.AppendToMapping("KeyboardInsets", (handler, view) =>
    {
        if (handler.PlatformView?.RootView is Android.Views.View rootView)
        {
            ViewCompat.SetOnApplyWindowInsetsListener(rootView, new KeyboardInsetsListener(handler));
        }
    });
#endif
});
```

Then add the listener class:

```csharp
#if ANDROID
class KeyboardInsetsListener : Java.Lang.Object, IOnApplyWindowInsetsListener
{
    private readonly Microsoft.Maui.Handlers.PageHandler _handler;

    public KeyboardInsetsListener(Microsoft.Maui.Handlers.PageHandler handler)
        => _handler = handler;

    public WindowInsetsCompat OnApplyWindowInsets(Android.Views.View view, WindowInsetsCompat insets)
    {
        var imeInsets = insets.GetInsets(WindowInsetsCompat.Type.Ime());
        var navInsets = insets.GetInsets(WindowInsetsCompat.Type.NavigationBars());
        int bottomPadding = Math.Max(imeInsets.Bottom - navInsets.Bottom, 0);

        if (_handler.PlatformView is Android.Views.View platformView)
        {
            platformView.SetPadding(0, 0, 0, bottomPadding);
        }

        return insets;
    }
}
#endif
```

## 3. Layout your chat screen

Use a `Grid` so the input bar naturally sits at the bottom and the message list shrinks when padding changes:

```xml
<Grid RowDefinitions="*, Auto">
    <CollectionView Grid.Row="0" ItemsSource="{Binding Messages}" ... />
    <HorizontalStackLayout Grid.Row="1" Padding="8">
        <Entry Placeholder="Type a message..." HorizontalOptions="FillAndExpand" />
        <Button Text="Send" />
    </HorizontalStackLayout>
</Grid>
```

**Why this works:** Instead of relying on the deprecated resize mode, you're listening to `WindowInsets` for the IME (keyboard) and manually adjusting padding. This is the same approach Android's own Jetpack libraries recommend. The input bar shifts up by exactly the keyboard height, and the `CollectionView` shrinks to fit.

**iOS** handles this automatically — no extra work needed there.
